William Hurt, a four-time Academy Award nominee who won Best Actor for his performance in Kiss of The Spider Woman, died Sunday, according to Deadline and other news reports. Hurt’s son confirmed the news in a statement, according to Deadline, saying the 71-year-old actor died of natural causes. Hurt had been diagnosed with terminal prostate cancer in 2018. Hurt starred in a string of acclaimed films during the 1980s, including The Big Chill, Broadcast News, Body Heat and Children of a Lesser God, earning three Best Actor nominations during the decade. He received a fourth nomination, for Best Supporting Actor, for 2005′s A History of Violence. Hurt also had a multi-film role in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, playing military leader Thaddeus Ross in a handful of Avengers and other Marvel films. Other hit films included The Village, Syriana, The Good Shepherd and Jane Eyre. On television, Hurt received Emmy and Golden Globe nominations for his roles in the drama series Damages and television movie Too Big To Fail, playing former Treasury secretary Henry Paulson. Tributes poured in from colleagues and costars on social media. “Working with him on Broadcast News was amazing,” tweeted Albert Brooks. “He will be greatly missed.” “I admired his acting so much and watching his commitment in person was remarkable,” tweeted his Too Big To Fail costar Topher Grace. “Another major loss to the acting community,” tweeted Mark Ruffalo, who starred as the Incredible Hulk alongside Hurt in multiple Marvel movies. “Great actor. Great mind. RIP.”